re families can bring their meals to be cooked. This enables even those without proper cooking facilities to participate in the tradition, reinforcing social cohesion and support among the less affluent members of the community. The baker thus acts both as a practical resource and a social linchpin, ensuring no family is excluded from the festivities due to poverty or lack of resources [Data: Entities (249); Relationships (394)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Dinner-Carriers Exemplify Shared Tradition and Festive Participation\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Individuals termed 'dinner-carriers'—often members of the town—are responsible for bringing their meals to the baker's shop, underscoring the communal aspects of the holiday tradition. This collective movement through the streets to prepare for the Christmas meal demonstrates the widespread observance of the practice and helps to foster a sense of belonging and shared ritual among townspeople. The dinner-carriers serve as a visible, communal link between private familial celebrations and the broader social fabric [Data: Entities (256); Relationships (400, 399)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Inclusion of the Townspeople in the Christmas Tradition\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The people of the town, as a collective, actively participate in the Christmas festivities, not only through church attendance but also through the dinner-carrying and communal dining rituals. Their involvement illustrates the tradition’s reach beyond individual families, transforming Christmas dinner into a widespread social event that binds the entire community. This collective participation also strengthens social bonds and ensures festive cheer is accessible to all, regardless of status [Data: Entities (257); Relationships (399)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Significant Dishes Contribute to Holiday Meaning and Satisfaction\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The Cratchit family’s Christmas meal is detailed with specifi